✅ Step 1: Update System
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

Install required dependencies:

sudo apt install -y curl wget apt-transport-https ca-certificates gnupg lsb-release
✅ Step 2: Install Docker (Recommended Driver)

Minikube works best on servers using Docker driver.

Install Docker
sudo apt install -y docker.io

Enable & start Docker:

sudo systemctl enable docker
sudo systemctl start docker

Add your user to docker group (so you don’t need sudo):

sudo usermod -aG docker $USER

⚠️ Log out and log back in after this step.

Verify:

docker --version
✅ Step 3: Install kubectl

Download latest kubectl:

curl -LO "https://storage.googleapis.com/kubernetes-release/release/$(curl -s https://storage.googleapis.com/kubernetes-release/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"

Make it executable:

chmod +x kubectl
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/

Verify:

kubectl version --client
✅ Step 4: Install Minikube

Download latest Minikube binary:

curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64

Install it:

sudo install minikube-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/minikube

Verify installation:

minikube version
✅ Step 5: Start Minikube (Docker Driver)

Now start Minikube:

minikube start --driver=docker

If your server has limited RAM, you can control resources:

minikube start --driver=docker --memory=4096 --cpus=2

(Adjust based on your server specs)

✅ Step 6: Verify Cluster

Check nodes:

kubectl get nodes

Check pods:

kubectl get pods -A

You should see:

minikube   Ready   control-plane
✅ Step 7: Enable Useful Addons

Enable dashboard:

minikube addons enable dashboard

Enable metrics server:

minikube addons enable metrics-server
✅ Step 8: Access Dashboard (Server Environment)

Since Ubuntu Server has no GUI, use:

minikube dashboard --url

It will output something like:

http://127.0.0.1:xxxxx/api/v1/namespaces/kubernetes-dashboard/services/http:kubernetes-dashboard:/proxy/

Then create SSH tunnel from your local machine:

ssh -L 8001:127.0.0.1:xxxxx user@your-server-ip

Open browser:

http://localhost:8001
🔥 Optional: Auto-Start Minikube on Boot

Create systemd service:

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/minikube.service

Add:

[Unit]
Description=Minikube
After=docker.service
Requires=docker.service

[Service]
User=YOUR_USERNAME
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/minikube start --driver=docker
ExecStop=/usr/local/bin/minikube stop
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Enable:

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable minikube
⚠️ Common Issues
1️⃣ Docker permission denied

Fix:

newgrp docker
2️⃣ Insufficient memory

Start with:

minikube start --memory=2048
3️⃣ Cgroup v2 issue (Ubuntu 22+)

If error occurs:

sudo nano /etc/default/grub

Add to GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX:

systemd.unified_cgroup_hierarchy=0

Then:

sudo update-grub
sudo reboot


Step-by-Step Fix
1️⃣ First Check Docker

Since you're on Ubuntu Server, we’ll use Docker driver.

systemctl status docker

If not running:

systemctl start docker
systemctl enable docker

Verify:

docker --version
2️⃣ Start Minikube Properly

Now run:

minikube start --driver=docker

If your server has limited RAM:

minikube start --driver=docker --memory=4096 --cpus=2

Wait until you see:

Done! kubectl is now configured to use "minikube"
3️⃣ Verify Cluster
kubectl get nodes

Expected output:

NAME       STATUS   ROLES           AGE   VERSION
minikube   Ready    control-plane   Xs    v1.xx.x



Run Minikube as a Normal User (NOT root)
Step 1 — Exit root
exit

You should now see something like:

youruser@Ubunto:~$

If you don't have a normal user, create one:

adduser devops
usermod -aG sudo devops
usermod -aG docker devops

Then:

su - devops
Step 2 — Ensure Docker works without sudo

Test:

docker ps

If permission denied:

sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
Step 3 — Start Minikube

Now run:

minikube start --driver=docker

This should work perfectly.

Then:

kubectl get nodes
🚨 Alternative (Not Recommended But Possible)

If you insist on running as root:

minikube start --driver=docker --force


